<paragraph id="AF61949200B3725ADD3316166E44FEBD" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
The flowers of 
<taxonomicName id="E6C81B361DB5812B604D3BB8E5AD481A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="62FC0FF02027FED5F24C15436B0EB988" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are often photographed because of their conspicuous clusters of brightly colored purple-red corolla tubes with contrasting green lobes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DD3E29F428279640A1CF7D1A09B296E3" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Kohleria affinis (Fritsch) Roalson &amp; Boggan A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A Clark et al. 7698 B Clark s. n. C Clark et al. 12979 D Clark et al. 15845). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564817" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">1</figureCitation>
). It is common to see individuals with 50+ pendent flowers, especially in abandoned cow pastures or recently cleared forests. Herbarium specimens do not preserve floral colors and most corollas dry uniformly black. Thus, corolla colors are challenging to determine on dried herbarium specimens unless noted by collectors in the descriptions. Use of field-based images, review of taxonomic literature, and examination of type specimens provided information for re-assessing the circumscription of 
<taxonomicName id="1749B27B35FBC94B25F1FA5B90CCA483" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="52012DBBE26F39AF8E6ABF7480241984" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="2E293E34D792D1162314E0FF79F98E9E" genus="K." lsidName="K. andina" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="B59E84B4AB0CB771BDAEFBD56DEBE71A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7BB2914FA740427DED972C9DF8C6C421" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
The corolla tube of 
<taxonomicName id="6DEF8AA4B3BD1CA83E9646BCC2E3F227" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="53095B081A6FE92465F2DA19A775FAFB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is white, but appears bright yellow from dense tomentose yellow trichomes (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F4A934ABAF1288149D7E4B1CC3186855" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Kohleria andina (Fritsch) J. L. Clark &amp; Jost A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A-D Clark et al. 7750). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564818" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">2</figureCitation>
). In contrast, the corolla tube of 
<taxonomicName id="308DA45168A40E6A86A3FE4E212F082A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="2766DCD47A2E2E4C8D9154E7FB78A121" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is dark red to bright purple (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5B6EC3C2B273D3F54D0195005D25A4F4" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Kohleria affinis (Fritsch) Roalson &amp; Boggan A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A Clark et al. 7698 B Clark s. n. C Clark et al. 12979 D Clark et al. 15845). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564817" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">1</figureCitation>
). The corolla tube in most 
<taxonomicName id="3D5535B8EC7BF9B8C3AE5A7D49DD71BE" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="B1EF9877EDD9E5E85934996587C6BA0E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is narrow, but some populations from Colombia are broad. The corolla tube of 
<taxonomicName id="D5680FB3C4E6E16309FFABEFE78F5AA1" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="7D62B1DA41A140C507B73C62A76F117D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is consistently broad. Corolla length in 
<taxonomicName id="D4A800FDEE526A1BF84363A3563410D5" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="948F9A5BA103480E582F166598DC4570" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is highly variable and ranges from 3 to 6 cm. In contrast, the corolla tubes of 
<taxonomicName id="11EEE4ABF2A45E5C6A069290BDE71F07" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="1DDD2EDA6B8A72B501779FAC16152614" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually less than 3.5 cm long. Both species have bright green corolla lobes that contrast with dark purple spots on the inner surface (Figs 
<figureCitation id="178AE9DB49AFE9473D6FC4D864FBC223" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Kohleria affinis (Fritsch) Roalson &amp; Boggan A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A Clark et al. 7698 B Clark s. n. C Clark et al. 12979 D Clark et al. 15845). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564817" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A95445AFC32AA9F44591B0EC889E7312" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Kohleria andina (Fritsch) J. L. Clark &amp; Jost A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A-D Clark et al. 7750). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564818" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="9862EF0916235A7EBB808867558C0AC7" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564818" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
