<paragraph id="E184EE6096F99B8550135B8480D47A1C" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
An additional character useful for differentiating 
<taxonomicName id="83DE63C55439170087F59901391C7772" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="006B507940EC22D2A6D0137E25B3C831" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="C192EA42030D7127AB9BD5559D1F6BA1" genus="K." lsidName="K. affinis" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="2845F835A4BAB87B862B87FA9117C43E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the presence of dark red-purple trichomes on the peduncles and pedicels (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="342D2F7D3D79A5E18C12CEC7E4833764" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Kohleria andina (Fritsch) J. L. Clark &amp; Jost A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A-D Clark et al. 7750). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564818" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">2A, D</figureCitation>
). The red-purple trichomes on the peduncles were noted by 
<bibRefCitation id="C82F6DC0D30311FD2723FEE21FC62312" author="Fritsch, K" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" pagination="392 - 439" refId="B3" refString="Fritsch, K, 1913. Gesneriaceae. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gesnerioideae. Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie 50: 392 - 439" title="Gesneriaceae. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gesnerioideae." volume="50" year="1913">Fritsch (1913</bibRefCitation>
: page 432) in the protologue, &quot;Pedunculi axillares elongati purpureo-villosi.&quot; In contrast, the peduncles in 
<taxonomicName id="0370FC4B1C9B083CA1513448A05AD634" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="9411EB620D6878AB1C311B74FB038A53" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sparsely pilose and appear green due to transparent trichomes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6982F54E489C00372979E8D8C054D2C6" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
<taxonomicName id="888036694401CBFEC659642EB34A5A1B" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="B77EA31A49F834611D9A4E7CD8DF6F53" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="181FFBFC9432200B80D352461BD42102" genus="K." lsidName="K. affinis" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="28D8B415C2EAD38F2ADE7427F36329BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are geographically separated by elevation. 
<taxonomicName id="E35D394FC5EEC8F4256D3F4166C9C761" genus="K." lsidName="K. andina" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="60412B286D6A35CCFB08A47BF6286699" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to elevations above 2500 meters on the western Andean slopes (Cordillera Oriental) in the Tungurahua province of Ecuador. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName id="172F94EB76F29CF3DE43873B1FCF633B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="88F9B50FB6E0EC941ECDBD7624A74B7A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in the northern Andes of Colombia (Antioquia, 
<normalizedToken id="96F606D18DCEEB6A75A5BE7C65144A50" originalValue="Boyacá">Boyaca</normalizedToken>
, Caldas, 
<normalizedToken id="A271D9943478F732FEADB04336859784" originalValue="Caquetá">Caqueta</normalizedToken>
, Cauca, 
<normalizedToken id="CEFAB52F09841FF47AED5DED580CBA2F" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
, Cundimarca, Huila, 
<normalizedToken id="6540081E7891F8FDD1C69A49700A54B4" originalValue="Nariño">Narino</normalizedToken>
, Putumayo, 
<normalizedToken id="E69FE0E02C64A2741D86EA920A4D1153" originalValue="Quindío">Quindio</normalizedToken>
, Risaralda, and Valle del Cauca), Ecuador (Azuay, 
<normalizedToken id="982E0E8C518A27B3AC31EA9AA96C4893" originalValue="Bolívar">Bolivar</normalizedToken>
, Carchi, Chimborazo, Cotopaxi, Esmeraldas, Imbabura, Loja, Napo, Pichincha, Santo Doingo, Tungurahua, and Zamora-Chinchipe), and northern Peru (Amazonas and Cajamarca). The 
<normalizedToken id="1009D1D526AED3028F5295816AE8E589" originalValue="authors’">authors'</normalizedToken>
field work from the upper slopes of Tungurahua, an active volcano in the western Andean slopes of the Cordillera Oriental, revealed little overlap. 
<taxonomicName id="8B3828F7787E969480D038335A7A2F5B" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="A79132C6C444D54F979C8BE6CFCEBA5D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is locally endemic to elevations above 2500 meters and 
<taxonomicName id="B1D6E6E5FAB659732D1FC64DF1D161A8" genus="K." lsidName="K. affinis" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="21B939ED5B42E8CDCA92A87A6F455ED6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread and located in forests below 2500 meters. Intermediate forms were not found here, indicating that these two forms are geographically separated by elevation and supported as different biological species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9714123604594FC1D46DA1C883AD5023" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="lectotypification">
<paragraph id="F93A181A11029BF46E01AD21B0CD3687" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Lectotypification.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0BA2407FF9EFDE416BFBFC08F0F91A5E" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
Syntypes are from two distinct localities: 
<emphasis id="A1F13D6F3F1D6B710552CCF1904B9B60" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">F.C. Lehmann 4869</emphasis>
(F0060498) from Colombia and 
<emphasis id="8B0CAFCEE6003C39BE7AF358C1E7C846" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">R. Spruce 5178</emphasis>
from K (K000395097) from Tungurahua, Ecuador. The specimen of 
<emphasis id="1D747B970F71F5FD5A3C7E03E3DDB12C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">F.C. Lehmann 4869</emphasis>
(F) is more similar to the widespread 
<taxonomicName id="5A1286919C27486F34B3913FF303BCC3" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria affinis" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="E51BE1516AF99D80674435786AEEF628" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimen of 
<emphasis id="9DAF8800B594F5EC144B281F14BBA3B4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">R. Spruce 5178</emphasis>
from (K) is similar to the locally endemic 
<taxonomicName id="2135337C347418935BE193549708C092" authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; Jost" baseAuthorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Kohleria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kohleria andina" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis id="4046CEC7377182E75595E25B5264FC3E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Kohleria andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and is designated as the lectotype to stabilize this species concept. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="82F0E232424A1CC26F70B0C35F2BD271" author="Fritsch, K" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" pagination="392 - 439" refId="B3" refString="Fritsch, K, 1913. Gesneriaceae. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gesnerioideae. Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie 50: 392 - 439" title="Gesneriaceae. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Gesnerioideae." volume="50" year="1913">Fritsch (1913)</bibRefCitation>
, Richard Spruce cites Tunguarahua as a locality and the specimens have characters that are congruent with the Tungurahua populations featured in the images here (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A374040BD63006A7EB305EE42031F883" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Kohleria andina (Fritsch) J. L. Clark &amp; Jost A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A-D Clark et al. 7750). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564818" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">2</figureCitation>
). The lectotype has a corolla that is wide and more ampliate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B77BC8F8F300B8290F3B786133625DAB" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Kohleria andina (Fritsch) J. L. Clark &amp; Jost A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A-D Clark et al. 7750). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564818" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">2</figureCitation>
) relative to the narrower corolla tube of 
<taxonomicName id="BF74F6C6FA5C2059C9BF2715BBB1496D" genus="K." lsidName="K. affinis" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="B19CB940C1D54F1A4D02E10CD586805D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="3C0C792202CFF6FE8F3C4EBBE561FDB5" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Kohleria affinis (Fritsch) Roalson &amp; Boggan A lateral view of flower B female phase of mature flower C male phase of mature flower D habit (A Clark et al. 7698 B Clark s. n. C Clark et al. 12979 D Clark et al. 15845). Photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.179.65990.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564817" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">1</figureCitation>
). An additional character that is congruent with material from the type locality and the lectotype (
<emphasis id="C0C9FC70879425A9C1B592DA95EE5B89" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">R. Spruce 5178</emphasis>
) is the presence of dark red trichomes on the peduncles and pedicels. In contrast, the peduncle and pedicel trichomes on 
<emphasis id="0089A92DAF09B85E0A1625B59BF8D09E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">F.C. Lehmann 4869</emphasis>
are transparent and more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="A16720572C418B46442C548B6756C97F" genus="K." lsidName="K. affinis" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="affinis">
<emphasis id="DBE70926C5B420C48C6F8BAE4992C19F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">K. affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
